{{equipment}}
[[Image:Swiss fondue 2.jpg|right|280px|Caquelon]] A '''Caquelon''' {{IPA|kakə'lõː}} <fr.> , (in some languages '''Gagglon''' or '''Gagglo'''),<ref> [[w:de:Caquelon]]</ref> is a cooking vessel of stoneware, ceramic, enamelled cast iron, or porcelain for the preparation of [[Cookbook:Fondue|fondue]].
The word is from a Swiss French term originating in the 18th century derived from the Swiss German word ''Kakel'' meaning an earthenware [[Cookbook:Pots and Pans#Enameled Cast Iron|casserole]]. The term is in common use throughout Switzerland, and in the Franche-Comté and [[Cookbook:Cuisine of France#Provence|Provençale]] regions of France.<ref>[[w:wiktionary:fr:Caquelon]]</ref><ref> ''Dictionnaire historique de la langue française'', Dictionnaires Le Robert, Paris</ref>
The bottom of a caquelon requires a thickness sufficient to prevent burning of the melted cheese when the vessel is placed over a spirit burner at the table. Nevertheless, an encrusted layer of cheese forms on the bottom called the ''Grossmutter'' in German, ''La Religieuse'' in French, which is released when the fondue has been consumed and is shared between the diners.
